How to negotiate net terms with your vendors – Credit Starts Here Login How to negotiate net terms with your vendors By underwriter Nov How to negotiate net terms with your vendors Underwritr Staff November , As a buyer, knowing how to negotiate with a supplier can strengthen your relationship, reduce the total cost of acquisition, and even provide availability if supply becomes Play the “long game”. If you are relying on a supplier for multiple or repeat purchases, you want terms that work in both the short and long Therefore, the deal needs to be beneficial to both It’s an obvious statement, until you start Understand what the supplier values If a supplier is focused on reducing Days Sales Outstanding (DSO), you may be able to get 2 10 Net , which means you can take a 2% discount if you pay the supplier invoice within days, otherwise you need to pay the full amount of the invoice within Although any combination of discount and due date is possible, 2 10 Net is still However, not all suppliers are focused on Some suppliers may be motivated by locking in These suppliers may be able to significantly reduce their cost of goods sold (COGS) for manufacturing if they commit to more Most production benefits from Once a production line is set up, the marginal cost decreases with each unit Additionally, as more production is presold, the volatility of carrying costs All this translates into better pricing for you, if you are willing to commit to multiple purchases over Stay focused on what s best for the People can act irrationally during People blow up deals because they turn the negotiation into an “us vs them” Stay calm and stay There is a line where suppliers will walk away from business – get close to it, and if you cross that line, make sure you can get the negotiation back on If a supplier believes you are negotiating in good faith, they’ll send you plenty of signals as to where that line Understand the market Know who their competitors You don’t need to necessarily bring them up in a negotiation – the supplier knows who their competition Come to the table prepared and knowledgeable, that is a strong signal to the supplier that you expect competitive Additionally, if you cannot come to an agreement, you can quickly pursue alternate In summary Having a strong supply chain is important to every company, whether it is a software company, a
